\ul Elevator Pitch (140 char max)\par
\ulnone\tab Argon microcontroller converts a 3-speed floor fan into a whole-house air circulation system. Buttons select manual/auto fan operation.\par
\ul Hackster.Io Story\ulnone\par
\f1\tab  This project repurposes a hi-\b p\b0 ower 3-\b s\b0 peed floor fan for its new role as a whole house attic fan. Fan power is provided by constructing  an active \b m\b0 ode PNP circuit connected to a relay switch, powered by an Argon Microcontroller. The fan circulates air throughout the house, concentrating into a custom-\b b\b0 uilt ceiling compartment that houses the fan,  which fans air out into the attic space, which then exits via open garage windows. \par
\tab The Argon is programmed for manual and automatic fan control operation. Manual mode operates just like an on-\b o\b0 ff switch. Automatic mode continuously checks for interior temperature or humidity exceeding their programmed thresholds beforing powering on the fan. Separate OLED screens show programmed menu button options to navigate and select the desired  mode. \par
\tab Once completing a working breadboard circuit, I began related work to complete the finalportion of the circuit: splicing the extension cord and soldering the spliced ends into the extended 14 ga wires connected to the COM ans NO conections of the tested breadboard circuit. After connecting the breaboard to the A/C circuit, I confirmed the fully completed circuit worked for manual andauto modes on Nov 6. This required plugging in a phone cord adapter cable from ther furnace closet power strip outlet to the microcontroller, for supplying power to the Argon, as well as connecting the fan's newly constructed power cord into the power strip to supply power to the fan, thus completing the entire circuit. The final phase of the project, constructing and installing PVC sheathing for the exposed power cord was completed on Nov. 11.\par
